            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Wong\u2019s San Francisco story isn\u2019t one of a tech boom transplant, but of deep, generational roots. His grandparents emigrated from Hong Kong in the 1960s, running a small but beloved grocery store in Chinatown. David grew up in the fog-drenched avenues of the Sunset District, the son of parents who revered education as the path away from the grueling hours of a family business. They saw his sharp mind and pushed him toward a more stable, corporate future.\n\nHe excelled, earning a business degree from UC Berkeley before pursuing his MBA at USC, a calculated move to accelerate his career. David entered the competitive world of retail as an assistant buyer, meticulously learning the trade. The 2008 financial crisis was his crucible; while others were laid off, David\u2019s knack for spotting value and understanding consumer anxiety helped his department stay afloat. This period solidified his reputation as a pragmatic, data-driven leader, paving his way to his current role as Director of Merchandising for a major apparel brand headquartered downtown.\n\nAt 46, David\u2019s life is one of structured success. A long-term relationship ended amicably a few years prior, shifting his focus inward and toward his career. His daily routine is disciplined: an early morning MUNI ride from his modern Hayes Valley condo, a day spent analyzing sales data and planning seasonal collections, followed by a workout at his gym. He rarely drives, finding the 1.1-mile public transit commute a moment of detachment from the city's chaos.\n\nDavid\u2019s connection to San Francisco is layered. He sees the ghosts of the city his grandparents knew while navigating the hyper-modern version he helps shape. His aspirations are no longer just about climbing the corporate ladder\u2014he\u2019s aiming for a Vice President title\u2014but about finding a deeper sense of balance. He dreams of traveling more, perhaps finding a partner who shares his appreciation for a quiet evening and a well-crafted meal, and honoring his family's legacy of hard work by finally allowing himself the time to truly enjoy the life it has provided him."
