            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the smell of dried shiitake mushrooms and dusty cardboard. Around age seven, he'd hide behind sacks of jasmine rice in his grandparents\u2019 store, listening to the clatter of the abacus and the melodic Cantonese chatter. It felt like the center of the universe. The memory is a stark, earthy contrast to the sleek minimalism of his current life. It grounds him, a reminder of the foundation upon which his ambition was built, a legacy of tangible goods and tireless community service.\n\n2.\nHe was sixteen, hunched over a calculus textbook at the kitchen table in the Sunset. His father came home, smelling of produce and exhaustion. He didn\u2019t say a word, just placed his calloused hand next to David's on the table. The contrast was a silent, powerful sermon. In that moment, David\u2019s ambition crystallized from a personal goal into a solemn duty. Succeeding wasn't just about escaping the store; it was about honoring the hands that built his opportunity.\n\n3.\nThe office was a ghost town in late 2008. David, then a junior buyer, remembers the eerie silence punctuated by the hum of his monitor. He stayed late, poring over sales data, searching for a thread of logic in the panic. He felt a cold knot of fear, but also a surge of clear-headed purpose. Keeping his department afloat wasn't just a job; it was survival. That crucible forged his reliance on data over instinct, a pragmatic shield he\u2019s carried ever since.\n\n4.\nA month after the amicable split, the silence of his Hayes Valley condo felt deafening. He remembers meticulously preparing a braised duck, a recipe for two, just for himself. As he sat at his small table, the initial pang of loneliness was replaced by a quiet, profound sense of peace. It wasn't about loss, but about rediscovery. That solitary, well-crafted meal marked the beginning of his inward turn, the search for a happiness that wasn't dependent on another person's presence.\n\n5.\nOn his MUNI ride to work last spring, the train paused, framing a perfect, jarring view: a new, glass-and-steel tower looming behind a faded, tile-roofed family association building. He felt a sense of temporal vertigo, seeing both the city his grandparents built and the one he helps shape. He wasn't just a passenger but a living bridge between them. This daily glimpse crystallized his desire not just to succeed in the new city, but to find a way to truly live in it."
